#!/usr/bin/env sh
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local pre-commit 3-gate chain (CLAUDE.md §1.6, TODO.md R0005).
#
# Mirrors the CI workflow in `.github/workflows/ci.yml`:
#
#   Gate 1 (format-staged-cs):           dotnet format --verify-no-changes
#                                        (read-only style check)
#   Gate 2 (build-warnings-as-errors):   dotnet build  -p:TreatWarningsAsErrors=true
#                                        (compiler + analyzers)
#   Gate 3 (run-tests):                  fast unit tests (Core + Application + Architecture)
#
# All three gates are defined in `.husky/task-runner.json` under
# `group: "pre-commit"`. This wrapper simply delegates to Husky's task runner so
# the gate definitions live in ONE place (the JSON manifest) instead of being
# duplicated between this shell script and CI. Husky's task runner handles
# cross-platform invocation (PowerShell on Windows, /bin/sh on Linux/macOS)
# without us having to hand-roll branching here.
#
# Slow test projects -- Infrastructure (Testcontainers), Api (WebApplicationFactory),
# E2E (Playwright), Web (bUnit) -- run only in CI. Pre-commit must stay under
# ~10-15 s to avoid being bypassed; CI is the safety net for the full suite.
#
# Cardinal rule: the format gate is read-only (`--verify-no-changes`). If it
# fails, the contributor must run `dotnet format` themselves and re-stage --
# we never auto-rewrite tracked files behind a commit.
#
# Bypass (use sparingly): `HUSKY=0 git commit -m "..."` skips the chain.
# CI will catch anything bypassed locally.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
. "$(dirname -- "$0")/_/husky.sh"

dotnet husky run --group pre-commit
